index of 22 kg/m\u00b2","Maternal age of 25 years","Nulliparity","Previous uncomplicated pregnancy","Singleton pregnancy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENulliparity\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the strongest risk factors for developing pre-eclampsia. First pregnancies carry a 2-3 times higher risk compared to subsequent pregnancies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevious uncomplicated pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E actually reduces the risk of pre-eclampsia in subsequent pregnancies\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebody mass index of 22 kg/m\u00b2\u003C/strong\u003E is within normal range and not associated with increased risk. Obesity (BMI \u0026gt;30 kg/m\u00b2) increases pre-eclampsia risk\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ematernal age of 25 years\u003C/strong\u003E is not a risk factor. Advanced maternal age (\u0026gt;35 years) increases risk\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esingleton pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E carries lower risk than multiple pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther significant risk factors include chronic hypertension, diabetes, autoimmune conditions, and family history of pre-eclampsia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nulliparity, multiple pregnancy, obesity, and pre-existing hypertension are major risk factors for pre-eclampsia","Pre-eclampsia risk is increased in women with autoimmune conditions like systemic lupus erythematosus"],"references":["Fox R, Kitt J, Leeson P, Aye CYL, Lewandowski AJ. Preeclampsia: Risk Factors, Diagnosis, Management, and the Cardiovascular Impact on the Offspring. J Clin Med. 2019 Oct 4;8(10):1625. doi: 10.3390/jcm8101625. PMID: 31590294; PMCID: PMC6832549.","Uzan J, Carbonnel M, Piconne O, Asmar R, Ayoubi JM. Pre-eclampsia: pathophysiology, diagnosis, and management. Vasc Health Risk Manag. 2011;7:467-74. doi: 10.2147/VHRM.S20181. Epub 2011 Jul 19. PMID: 21822394; PMCID: PMC3148420.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52733"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15968"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52733"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T15:57:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T15:58:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8659"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67281"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null